<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'line-height:115%'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.25in'><span style=3D'line-height=
:115%'>For
example, assume the state minimum wage is $7.50 and that the state law requ=
ires
a cash wage of $2.13 per hour and allows the employer to take a tip credit =
of
$5.37 per hour.&nbsp; Assuming all hours worked during the week were at the
state minimum wage rate, the employee’s regular rate is the state minimum w=
age
rate ($7.50) but the employer is limited to a tip credit of $5.12 under the
FLSA ($7.25 &#8211; $2.13). See 29 CFR 778.5.&nbsp; The employer must make =
up
the difference between the Sec. 6(a)(1) minimum wage and the regular rate in
cash before calculating the additional half time due.&nbsp; See FOH32j02.</=
span></p>

